body:
[CS1591](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/csharp/language-reference/compiler-messages/cs1591) - `Missing XML comment for publicly visible type or member 'Type_or_Member'`
**Version** - `MSBuild 17.4.0.51802`

### Brief description
Members that implement an interface member will implicitly apply `/// <inheritdoc/>` ([source](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/47436#issuecomment-686827033)) - and this works as expected. However, `CS1591` is still issued for such members (unless `/// <inheritdoc/>` is explicitly added).

### Sample

Hovering `Foo.Bar` in the following sample displays `The bar.` - but `CS1591` is also issued for `Foo.Bar`.

```csharp
// in .csproj: <GenerateDocumentationFile>true</GenerateDocumentationFile>

public interface IFoo
{
    /// <summary>The bar.</summary>
    int Bar { get; }
}

public class Foo : IFoo
{
    public int Bar => 2;
}
```

## Context
One of the steps to close the gap between the existing official build and the [.NET source-build](https://github.com/dotnet/source-build) is enabling prebuilt detection on the individual product repository level. 

Our goal is to introduce prebuilt detection on an individual product repo level so that developers could detect prebuilts during their PR validation and resolve the problem by generating the SBRPs themselves with minimum assistance from the A&D team. 

Unfortunately, the current [SPRB](https://github.com/dotnet/source-build-reference-packages/tree/main/src/referencePackageSourceGenerator) (Source Build Reference Package generation tooling), [GenAPI](https://github.com/dotnet/arcade/tree/main/src/Microsoft.DotNet.GenAPI), is not sufficient for this scenario as it uses the old Microsoft Common Compiler Infrastructure (Microsoft CCI) to generate the API surface for individual packages. The Microsoft CCI backend needs to be periodically updated to reflect the latest language changes which is often a time-consuming task requiring significant expertise.

We developed a [Roslyn-based GenAPI](https://github.com/dotnet/sdk/tree/main/src/GenAPI) tool that aims to replace the CCi-based version. During the testing we found several bugs in the API (Workspaces) all summarized at [Summary of issues found during testing of the Roslyn-based GenAPI](https://github.com/dotnet/arcade/issues/12009) issue in dotnet/arcade.

---

**Version Used**: 4.5.0-3.22601.3 (~main)

**Steps to Reproduce**:
Issue: on our side: https://github.com/dotnet/arcade/issues/10526

Example:
```C#
public abstract partial class A
{
    public abstract TResult? Accept<TResult>(int a);
}

public sealed partial class B : A
{
    public override TResult? Accept<TResult>(int a) where TResult : default { throw null; }
}
```
After roundtrip: source -> ISymbol-> SyntaxGenerator -> source:
```C#
public abstract partial class A
{
    public abstract TResult? Accept<TResult>(int a);
}
public sealed partial class B : A
{
    /// error CS0508: 'B.Accept<TResult>(int)': return type must be 'TResult' to match overridden member 'A.Accept<TResult>(int)'
    /// error CS0453: The type 'TResult' must be a non-nullable value type in order to use it as parameter 'T' in the generic type or method 'Nullable<T>'
    public override TResult? Accept<TResult>(int a) { throw null; }
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:

**Expected Behavior**:

**Actual Behavior**:

*I don't know if this behavior is intentional to address some corner case I'm not seeing; if it is, please forgive this erroneous bug report*

Changing only the type of a property from a simple struct to a nullable version of the same struct either changes (if this isn't a bug) or breaks (if this is a bug) same-name type resolution. This is inconsistent with the behavior observed when the property is a regular value type, a reference type, or a nullable reference type.

**Version Used**: 

Visual Studio 17.0.0 Preview 5.0 with a C# 10 project.

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
public class Foo {
    public TimeSpan? TimeSpan => TimeSpan.FromDays(7);
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

The compiler will be able to deduce that in `TimeSpan.FromDays()` the token `TimeSpan` refers to a type and not the instance by the same name.

**Actual Behavior**:

An error is observed as `TimeSpan` is resolved to the property by that name and not the type with that name, and an instance of `TimeSpan` does not have a `FromDays()` function.

Note that this behavior only occurs for a nullable value type, and is not observed with any of the other possible combinations. The following all compile OK:

```csharp
public class Foo {
    public TimeSpan TimeSpan => TimeSpan.FromDays(7);
    public string String => String.IsNullOrEmpty(null) ? "foo" : "bar";
    public Array? Array => Array.BinarySearch(new object[] { }, null) == 0 ? new object[] { } : new object[] { };
}
```

The above are all able to correctly resolve a non-namespaced reference to a type by the same name as the property to the type (yielding access to the static method within).

Code like
```csharp
var x = new { p: "data" };
var y = x switch {
    { p: "123" } => 1,
    { p: "data"} => 2,
    _ => 3,
};
```
all end up on the same line after latest release, like this:
```csharp
var x = new { p: "data" };
var y = x switch { { p: "123" } => 1, { p: "data"} => 2,
    _ => 3,
};
```
Since this looks really bad I assume it is a bug. But if it is a breaking change, what setting should we update to get the former style?
We use .editorconfig from dotnet runtime plus the change: `csharp_new_line_before_open_brace=methods, types`. Do we need to add some new parameter here for switch expressions or patterns? We could not find any setting that made sense for switch/pattern.

