```

`Program.cs`:
```cs
class Testing {
    private bool Test(out object thing) {
        thing = new object();
        return true;
    }
    private static void Thingy(Testing testing) {
        object obj;
        if (testing?.Test(out obj) == true) {
            obj.ToString();
        }
    }
    private static void Main() => Thingy(new Testing());
}
```

I _believe_ that this **should fail** compilation, with the error `error CS0165: Use of unassigned local variable 'obj'`, because LangVersion is 6.0. For example, this was reported as happening in https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/45776, and the response was "this is intended behavior, file a language change if you want to change the behavior", which I believe eventually turned into the C#10 Improved Definite Assignment Analysis feature.

However, compilation **succeeds** using visual studio `17.0.5`, C# tools `4.0.1-1.21568.1+6ab6601178d9fba8c680b56934cd1742e0816bff`, even though LangVersion is set to 6.0. (I cycled down through language versions from 9.0 to 6.0, and stopped at 6.0 because that's when `?.` was introduced. All succeeded compilation.)

When using an **old** compiler, set to language version 9.0 - e.g. how I discovered this, the one in Unity 2021.2.7f1, or the one currently [online on sharplab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:C4LglgNgNAJiDUAfAAgJgAQBUCmBnYYAdgOboDeAsAFDq3oAOATmAG4CGw26ARgPa8QseYAApeAV2Dpe3AFbYAxlOAALIsQCU5anV3pV69AF50hbAHdpcxaI0BuHXtrIA7PsbjsDmnQC+j2iZWDi5kAEYANnRkABYsNRIATxEcfENONJItSh8nGXklK1lvJ1owADN0EQyCEgB+ADpU0QkpfK0jE2APbGyA0tp8pt4AZW71EXt+3X9c9FndIPZOaMjouIBZNiJJ4wA+ePVks0tmiY0pqlmgA=), compilation **fails** (as it should).

Thanks for your time!

