I am able to reproduce this behaviour with every version >= 4.5.5 available in the playground. There are no FAQ entries that mention `7051`.

### ⏯ Playground Link

1. [5.1.6](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ts=5.1.6#code/GYVwdgxgLglg9mABAEzgZTgWwKZQBYxgDmAFMAFyIkB0tYImARtgE4DaAugJSIC8AfInABrMHADuYHgG8AsAChEiFrhAskwEgEYANIgBMegMxcA3AoC+QA)
2. [5.2.0 beta](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ts=5.2.0-dev.20230713#code/GYVwdgxgLglg9mABAEzgZTgWwKZQBYxgDmAFMAFyIkB0tYImARtgE4DaAugJSIC8AfInABrMHADuYHgG8AsAChEiFrhAskwEgEYANIgBMegMxcA3AoC+QA)

### 💻 Code

```ts
function doSomething(f: (...number[]) => unknown) {
  //                     ~~~~~~~~~~
  // Parameter has a name but no type. Did you mean 'arg0: number[]'? (7051)
  return f(1, 2, 3);
}
```

Quick-fixed:

```ts
function doSomething(f: (...arg0: number[][]) => unknown) {
  return f(1, 2, 3);
  //       ~
  // Argument of type 'number' is not assignable to parameter of type 'number[]'. (2345)
}
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior

The suggestion is correct. However, `number[]` gets converted to `number[][]`.

### 🙂 Expected behavior

`(...number[]) => unknown` becomes `(...arg0: number[]) => unknown`.

# Bug Report

In this example using a recursive generic type, the `b` prop of the second `createFoo` is inferred to be `unknown`. 

```ts
type FooConfig<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: {
    [P in keyof T[K]]: number | ((f: Foo<T>) => number);
  }
}

type Foo<T> = {
  [K in keyof T]: {
    [P in keyof T[K]]: number;
  }
};

const createFoo = <T, TFoo = Foo<T>>(args: FooConfig<T>): TFoo =>  {
  // code...
}

const foo = createFoo({
  a: {
    i: 1,
  },
  b: {
    ii: () => 1, // <-- no function arg, works as expected
  }
});

// works as intended
console.log('@-->foo', foo.b.ii);

const foo2 = createFoo({
  a: {
    i: 1,
  },
  b: {
    ii: (f) => f.a.i += 1, // <-- only difference is that this method has an argument
    // iii: 3 // <-- uncomment this line and it works
  }
});

// type error when function argument is present in config
console.log('@-->foo2', foo2.b.ii);
```

This example has two instances of the `createFoo` method. The first call is not using a function argument for the `b.ii` param and everything works as intended.

In the 2nd `createFoo` call, the `b.ii` param takes a method argument that is a recursive reference to the `createFoo` method argument itself.

The recursive reference type itself works as expected (i.e. the `f` in `b.ii` is typed correctly)

But in the resulting output, references to `foo2.b.ii` cause a type error.

Strangely, if I add a `b.iii` param as either a `number` or a `() => number` type (i.e. not using the recursive reference), then the `foo2.b.ii` type error is resolved.

### 🔎 Search Terms

* `recursive unknown`

### 🕗 Version & Regression Information

This bug is present in every version of TypeScript available in the TS Playground.

### ⏯ Playground Link

[Playground link with relevant code](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#-gli1FDnK9UIooYpwD4QDYPjgLBDGFAABRcCBrOBhWaaCNg0DYMAwW8vyrVcEBVUh6xqOoEGbVxWw5WgRygbtex7EIB2I4dRzQcdVw2KokKgABqUhJ3vBcl1QD4QCgc4MDQNAdG2a5mHBYAAAsaigaSMHBO5pLgc4oBk48tx6dRtmAId72Q0iAGZp1nbioHFIo1DuHY5KkhSoA+FhoCqd9mDKR8j2vctUPvXkzW0bQDwfKTtlXCyN1QUEtOssp7LASpLRs8JvxxSsfz-ACgJA8DIOg2lYIwukEKQlDsiAA)

### 💻 Code

See above

### 🙁 Actual behavior

The `foo2` instance results in the following `.d.ts`:

```ts
declare const foo2: Foo<{
    a: {
        i: unknown;
    };
    b: unknown;
}>;
```

<!-- What happened, and why it was wrong -->

### 🙂 Expected behavior

The `foo2` instance should result in something like this:

```ts
declare const foo2: Foo<{
    a: {
        i: unknown;
    };
    b: {
        ii: unknown;
    };
}>;
```

