### ⏯ Playground Link

N/A

### 💻 Code

1. Prepare a project that installs a custom `@typescript/lib-es5` package. (`npm i -D better-typescript-lib` is enough, for example)
2. Run below code.

```ts
import typescript from "typescript";

const program = typescript.createProgram({
  rootNames: ["src/ts-bug-check.ts"],
  options: {}
});

const sf = program.getSourceFile("node_modules/@typescript/lib-es5/index.d.ts");
if (!sf) throw new Error("!!!!")

// Should print true, actually prints false
console.log(program.isSourceFileDefaultLibrary(sf));
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior

`program.isSourceFileDefaultLibrary(sf)` returns false.

### 🙂 Expected behavior

`program.isSourceFileDefaultLibrary(sf)` should return true since that file is loaded in place of TypeScript's built-in `lib.es5.d.ts` file.

## 🗻 Context

https://github.com/typescript-eslint/typescript-eslint/issues/6207

TypeScript-ESLint uses `isSourceFileDefaultLibrary` to check whether an object is an instance of TypeScript's built-in `Error` class. However, if the rule is used with `better-typescript-lib` which installs `@typescript/lib-xxx` packages, it no longer works. 

> Then I guess that `isSourceFileDefaultLibrary` doesn't return true for the file because essentially its check boils down to `filename.startsWith('node_modules/typescript/lib/')`. IDK if that's a bug or intentional... regardless it's the behaviour!

