# Bug Report
When using Omit on a discriminated union type, the properties unique to each "branch" of the union type are lost.

### 🔎 Search Terms
Omit, union, discriminated union

### 🕗 Version & Regression Information
Tested on TypeScript 4.8.4 and on the nightly version (June 5th, 2023)

### ⏯ Playground Link
[demo](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ts=5.2.0-dev.20230605#code/C4TwDgpgBAKlC8UDeAoK6oHpNQMIHsBbQ-AOyjACd9JLgBLCAZzQ1IENCIAuKJ4SvVIBzADQpW6bFAAi9JgGNBhIe2D5KkqKEi8AjOK3SAqqXoBHAK7QqNCHUYsMFamD29+gkeIC+UAD7IRjgExGRQAAqu9gzMWhxcHgJCYhLO0nKKyqrqms46PFAATIbpOKYW1pHRDnHOtmBFSV6pPhLSMAAW8lA9AG7sADb0ACYoCmT8UPgARgBW7rAIQc4JhQDkswvr4vnghQZaDYvr-UOj6yhtKAWwRcsA8irAADwwolDra+sAfO04XR6QNIA2GIw+M0swF60KYnXwlkGIygM2goNGKIgCnYliY0AA7tAyIMQNNnsAIMjgJ1oAAiNa0lx2OggcaTaFbXgwe6IVB7XTFXYYBpNT7sGYKEY7K5AA)

[Alternative demo](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ts=5.2.0-dev.20230605#) (a different way to do discriminated unions, which is also affected)

### 💻 Code
```
type T = {
    name: string,
    type: 1,
    prop1: string,
} | {
    name: string,
    type: 2,
    prop2: string,
}

type T2 = Omit<T, 'name'>
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior
T2 is interpreted as such by TypeScript:
```
type T2 = {
    type: 1 | 2;
}
```

And the following object is seen as invalid:
```
const obj: T2 = {
    type: 2,
    prop2: 'abcd', // "prop2 does not exist on type T2"
}
```

### 🙂 Expected behavior
T2 should be interpreted like this instead:
```
type T2 = {
    type: 1;
    prop1: string;
} | {
    type: 2;
    prop2: string;
}
```
And the object described above should be seen as valid.

# Bug Report

Within the following code, I am able to pass an instance of `Foo` to `Bar1`'s constructor even though `Foo`'s `doSomething` method is not compatible with the type declared by `BarType1`.  Effectively, this could be a runtime error if `Foo.doSomething()` were to expect property `b` to have been assigned:
```ts
interface TestInterface<T> {
	doSomething(param: T): void;
}

type FooType = { a: string; b: string };
class Foo implements TestInterface<FooType> {
	public doSomething(param: FooType): void {}
}

type BarType1 = { a: string }; // subset of FooType
class Bar1 {
	private test: TestInterface<BarType1>;

	public constructor(test: TestInterface<BarType1>) {
		this.test = test;
	}

	public anotherThing(param: BarType1) {
		this.test.doSomething(param);
	}
}

type BarType2 = { c: string }; // disjoint of FooType
class Bar2 {
	private test: TestInterface<BarType2>;

	public constructor(test: TestInterface<BarType2>) {
		this.test = test;
	}

	public anotherThing(param: BarType2) {
		this.test.doSomething(param);
	}
}

type BarType3 = { a: string; b: string; c: string}; // superset of FooType
class Bar3 {
	private test: TestInterface<BarType3>;

	public constructor(test: TestInterface<BarType3>) {
		this.test = test;
	}

	public anotherThing(param: BarType3) {
		this.test.doSomething(param);
	}
}

type BarType4 = { a: string; c: string } // contains some members of FooType as well as additional members
class Bar4 {
	private test: TestInterface<BarType4>;

	public constructor(test: TestInterface<BarType4>) {
		this.test = test;
	}

	public anotherThing(param: BarType4) {
		this.test.doSomething(param);
	}
}

const bar1 = new Bar1(new Foo()); // Shouldn't this be an error?  Property b is missing from BarType1 but it's required in FooType.  I would expect the same error as in the bar4 example below.
const bar2 = new Bar2(new Foo()); // Error "Type 'BarType2' is missing the following properties from type 'FooType': a, b" -- errors as expected
const bar3 = new Bar3(new Foo()); // No error but that seems okay -- the Foo.doSomething() would just get an extra property passed
const bar4 = new Bar4(new Foo()); // Error "Property 'b' is missing in type 'BarType4' but required in type 'FooType'" -- This error looks correct, but I'm not sure why this is an error when bar1 was not.
```

I'm guessing this is an undesirable although expected behavior in TypeScript since I am able to replicate it as a problem in all versions supported by the TypeScript playground.  However, this behavior seems incorrect to me since TS correctly detects the error in the `Bar4` instance.

I reviewed the FAQ about `strictFunctionTypes` to see if that had any bearing, but the same non-error occurs when I use a function or arrow function which accepts a parameter that is of type `TestInterface<BarType1>`.

### 🔎 Search Terms

<!--
  What search terms did you use when trying to find an existing bug report?
  List them here so people in the future can find this one more easily.
-->

### 🕗 Version & Regression Information

- This is the behavior in every version I tried, and I reviewed the FAQ for entries about `strictFunctionTypes`.

### ⏯ Playground Link

[Playground link with relevant code](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?#--bMB2vTFb3A6MHzjJ8XyAqp33UzTLz-VkylfcyQOxNQ7S3AcHBEAZzBACBKKFPp+G83zgn4KQeTQ5BmC4Rgch8egQAAcgHJFHBQONkGgKAAQAfmQZAAAVMt7bRHFCQI2AVDBpRgTK2Cg3QBgcHIB2Y+LAigCAAEccmAdr6FCEAyJMZFcuwZBKOi2L0oAD10P4zmfWYxBQDKAXo0B5pQdyoFgiAprECIIGRDZ5LckQxS8nzdQCy7gtC2UZgAUSgTKoGQAAicj4qrEV4tK-CKulYlkBgRhaMYSjpUORgiuATBgZqs4OnijUIHiyQ4AAGkcN7kAAWlx9LnoBQJ-Gm2bIHoY7nUcERawu3ydmra6gsMEKwrlUae0ERgFnmhUlm8v7GAAazgLQsaB4J+qwOMkDGia+sVHIsGQXhFjS3akB1KGiq0KmVa22D6aFaDmaHNn7uQJ6XvegroegYr4ocX7+fKgJpXWyCvvU37GoHdqup6iA+s9pGUfinH8bQRlCZtnxDGFwJPmeiA-ixv3kGweLavjWYcnasauC0PnAn5jWideyjnwGraBko0n4yO6ggA)

### 💻 Code

<!-- Please post the relevant code sample here as well. This code and the Playground code should be the same, do not use separate examples -->
```ts
interface TestInterface<T> {
	doSomething(param: T): void;
}

type FooType = { a: string; b: string };
class Foo implements TestInterface<FooType> {
	public doSomething(param: FooType): void {}
}

type BarType = { a: string }; // subset of FooType
class Bar {
	private test: TestInterface<BarType>;

	public constructor(test: TestInterface<BarType>) {
		this.test = test;
	}

	public anotherThing(param: BarType) {
		this.test.doSomething(param);
	}
}

const bar = new Bar(new Foo()); // no error
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior

Construction of `bar1` does not emit a type error.


### 🙂 Expected behavior

Construction of `bar1` should emit `Property 'b' is missing in type 'BarType1' but required in type 'FooType'`

# Bug Report

I was working with a library which reported that a property had an additional value of `undefined`, and the author of the plugin claimed that the error went by removing `readonly`. After investigating I found the following, which I found confusing.

The framework we use (vue) has a function for marking objects as deeply readonly:
```ts
export declare function readonly<T extends object>(target: T): DeepReadonly<T>;
export declare type DeepReadonly<T> = T extends {} ? {
    readonly [K in keyof T]: DeepReadonly<T[K]>;
} : Readonly<T>;
```

When wrapping an object with optional properties:

```ts
export declare class User {
    a?: string;
    b: string;
}
export const user = readonly(new User() )
```

... the exported types have an additional `undefined` at the type definition, even though it wasn't allowed in the original type.

```ts
export declare class User {
    a?: string;
    b: string;
}
export declare const user: {
    readonly a?: string | undefined;
    readonly b: string;
};
```

### 🔎 Search Terms

extra undefined, nested readonly, deepreadonly

### 🕗 Version & Regression Information

- This is the behavior in every version I tried.

### ⏯ Playground Link

[Playground link with relevant code](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play?ts=5.2.0-beta#code/KYDwDg9gTgLgBAE2AYwDYEMrDgMwK4B2yMAlhAXFuguagJ4A8AKnKDMAQgM5wQBGAKxQwAfAAoYmAObAYALjhMAlAoAiwYGABKwarUZMRAbgBQoSLEQoMWODDphs6zTr0F6zEXAC8i1iHZOHgBvAF84AH44YJM4OMpdGnc6OABtAGk4EgoAa2A6CBxFAF01DW1E-WYM4uMTcIVXJI9DUzNwaHgkNExsHq4eAFUuYCho2Pj0CIUuGChsqVN4uD4ZuYXTUJN2iy7rXrsHbCaAeWTh0Z84Zwq3DwuoEW3zTrhkclm4PBGx3ypmuhiAjAADucAeYiUcCUJiAA)

### 💻 Code

This was the smallest I could reduce the code to and still see the compiler doing the unexpected:
```ts
export declare function readonly<T extends object>(target: T): DeepReadonly<T>;
export declare type DeepReadonly<T> = T extends {} ? {
    readonly [K in keyof T]: DeepReadonly<T[K]>;
} : Readonly<T>;

export declare class User {
    a?: string;
    b: string;
}

export declare type ReadOnlyUser = DeepReadonly<User>

export const user = readonly(new User() )
```

### 🙁 Actual behavior

The code above is transformed to the following types. The generated type for the variable `user` is incompatible with the exported class `User`, because it adds `undefined` as type to the type of the optional parameter of the class.
```ts
export declare const user: {
    readonly a?: string | undefined;
    readonly b: string;
};
```
### 🙂 Expected behavior

The types of `User` and `user` should be identical, the latter should just have all props as `readonly`, but there should be no other changes to the type.
```ts
export declare const user: {
    readonly a?: string;
    readonly b: string;
};
```

